n Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: (i) locative name from any of various places called  <i>Ashington</i> (especially Lincs, Sussex), or Ashingdon (Essex). (ii) possibly a variant of   Ashenden   in Kent contexts; note Robt.  <i>Ashinden</i>, 1730 in   IGI   (Deal, Kent)."],"variants":[{"name":"IGI","meanings":["1  Norman, English: probably a clipped form of   Dawnay  . Compare Bridgett Dawney, 1627, George Dawne, 1629, in   IGI   (Langar, Notts).  See also  Laney   and   Dando  . Some of the following early bearers could alternatively belong with (2) through family migration.","2  English: relationship name from Middle English  <i>Dawen</i>, a variant of   Dawes   with the weak declension genitival suffix  <i>-(e)n</i> (Old English  <i>-an</i>) instead of the standard Middle English  <i>-es</i>. The usage is mainly restricted to West Midlands dialects of Middle English."]},{"name":"Ashenden","meanings":["English: locative name from Ashenden in Tenterden (Kent), which is recorded as  <i>Esserinden'</i> in 1278."]}]},{"name":"Ellen","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Helen  , although now no longer associated with that name. Initial <i>H-</i> tended to be added and dropped rather capriciously, leading to many doublets (  compare for example  Esther   and   Hester  ). It is also sometimes used as a short form of   Eleanor  , to which, however, it is unrelated."],"variants":[{"name":"Eleanor","meanings":["From an Old French respelling of the Old Provençal name <i>Alienor</i>. This has sometimes been taken as a derivative of   Helen  , but it is more probably of Germanic derivation (the first element being <i>ali</i> ‘other, foreign’ the second is obscure). The name was introduced to England by  Eleanor of Aquitaine  (  1122–1204 ), who came from Aquitaine in south-west France to be the wife of  King Henry II . It was also borne by Eleanor of Provence, the wife of  Henry III , and Eleanor of Castile, wife of  Edward I ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Ellen Ashington was born in 1171, in Chilton, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom, her father, John Ashington, was 22 and her mother, Mrs. John Ashington, was 19. She married Richard Covert III about 1199, in Bramber, Sussex, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son."},"et":{"1171–":"1171–Surnud","1171–Female":"1171–Surnud","1148–1233":"1148–1233","1198–1280":"1198–1280","1150–1230":"1150–1230","1153–Female":"1153–Surnud","1148":"1148","Abt 1199":"umbes 1199","1233":"1233","1198":"1198","1153":"1153","1230":"1230","1150":"1150","1171":"1171","1280":"1280","Bramber, Sussex, England, United Kingdom":"Bramber, Sussex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Ashington Manor, Chilton, England":"Chilton, Oxfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Sullington, Sussex, England, United Kingdom":"Sullington, Sussex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1171–":"1171–Kuollut","1171–Female":"1171–Kuollut","1148–1233":"1148–1233","1198–1280":"1198–1280","1150–1230":"1150–1230","1153–Female":"1153–Kuollut","1148":"1148","Abt 1199":"noin 1199","1233":"1233","1198":"1198","1153":"1153","1230":"1230","1150":"1150","1171":"1171","1280":"1280","Bramber, Sussex, England, United Kingdom":"Bramber, Sussex, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Ashington Manor, Chilton, England":"Chilton, Oxfordshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Sullington, Sussex, England, United Kingdom":"Sullington, Sussex, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1171–":"1171–Décédée","1171–Female":"1171–Décédée","1148–1233":"1148–1233","1198–1280":"1198–1280","1150–1230":"1150–1230","1153–Female":"1153–Décédée","1148":"1148","Abt 1199":"environ 1199","1233":"1233","1198":"1198","1153":"1153","1230":"1230","1150":"1150","1171":"1171","1280":"1280","Bramber, Sussex, England, United Kingdom":"Bramber, Sussex, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Ashington Manor, Chilton, Engla